[[File:Krzywy Domek w Sopocie.jpg|238px|thumbnail|right|[[Sopot]], Crooked house]] {{Postmodernism}}
'''Polish postmodernism''' refers to the [[Polish culture|cultural]], artistic and [[Polish philosophy|philosophical]] development within the [[Poland|Polish society]] coinciding with the [[Revolutions of 1989|downfall of communism]] and the [[History of Poland (1989–present)#Round Table Agreement and democratic transition|democratic transitions]] leading to Poland's 2004 [[2004 enlargement of the European Union|accession into the European Union]].<ref name="Bolecki">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pV6sFB-KuU8C&lpg=PA51&dq=%22Two%20perspectives%20on%20the%201980s%20and%20after%22&pg=PA51#v=onepage&q=%22Two%20perspectives%20on%20the%201980s%20and%20after%22&f=false | title=1989 in Poland: Continuity and Caesura | publisher=John Benjamins Publishing | work=History of the Literary Cultures of East-Central Europe ''by Marcel Cornis-Pope and John Neubauer'' | year=2004 | accessdate=March 16, 2013 | author=Wlodzimierz Bolecki | pages=51–54 | isbn=9027234523 | format=Google book preview}}</ref>
==Background== The discourse on the philosophical concept and literary awareness of [[postmodernism]] appeared in Polish criticism long before the collapse of the Soviet Bloc, triggered by numerous publications of writers now characterized as postmodernist,<ref name="Anderson">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Origins_of_Postmodernity.html?id=zvmhePXJJ5gC | title=Cristallization | publisher=Verso | work=The Origins of Postmodernity | year=1998 | accessdate=March 22, 2013 | author=Perry Anderson | format=Google book preview}}</ref> including [[Jorge Luis Borges|Borges]], [[Kurt Vonnegut|Vonnegut]], [[Vladimir Nabokov|Nabokov]] as well as [[Raymond Federman|Federman]], [[John Hawkes (novelist)|Hawkes]] and [[Ihab Hassan|Hassan]] among others (separate anthologies).<ref name="Janaszek-Ivaničková" /> Already before the end of the 1970s [[Samuel Beckett]] was produced in Poland by over a dozen national theatres in seven metropolitan cities including primary TV broadcast in 1971. His ''[[En attendant Godot]]'' in translation premiered as far back as 1957 both in [[Warsaw]] (at ''Teatr Współczesny'') and in [[Kraków]] (''Teatr 38'').<ref name="e-teatr.pl">{{cite web | url=http://www.e-teatr.pl/pl/realizacje/423,sztuka.html | title=Author: Samuel Beckett | publisher=Instytut Teatralny im. Zbigniewa Raszewskiego | work=Baza realizacji&nbsp;– rejestr archiwów (Database) | year=2010 | accessdate=March 22, 2013 | author=Instytut Teatralny | language=Polish}}</ref> Polish postmodernism can be identified in the work of prolific poet and playwright [[Tadeusz Różewicz]], philosophers [[Leszek Kołakowski]], [[Stanisław Lem]], [[Tadeusz Kantor]], or in the output of various Polish émigré writers such as the Nobel laureate [[Czesław Miłosz]] (''[[The Captive Mind]]'') and his contemporaries including [[Witold Gombrowicz]].<ref name="Janaszek-Ivaničková">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n_Eqx2Gr1vUC&pg=PA425&dq=%22Witkacy,+Witold+Gombrowicz,+and+Karol+Irzykowski%22+%22postmodern+developments%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZvdHUYmwEOOjigLyrIGABw&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Witkacy%2C%20Witold%20Gombrowicz%2C%20and%20Karol%20Irzykowski%22%20%22postmodern%20developments%22&f=false | title=Postmodernism in Poland | work=International Postmodernism: Theory and Literary Practice | accessdate=March 18, 2013 | author=Halina Janaszek-Ivaničková | pages=423–427 | publisher=John Benjamins Publishing | year=1997 | isbn=9027234450}}</ref> The basis for the distinctiveness of Polish postmodernism were established [[avant la lettre]] already [[Polish culture in the Interbellum|in the Interbellum]] through controversial, though widely recognized works of [[Witkacy]] (the ''Golden Laurel'' of [[Polish Academy of Literature|PAL]], 1935),<ref name="Bulowska">{{cite web | url=http://literat.ug.edu.pl/autors/witkacy.htm | title=Stanisław Ignacy Witkiewicz | publisher=''Virtual Library of Polish Literature'' | accessdate=December 13, 2011 | author=Prof. dr hab. Miłosława Bulowska Schielman}}</ref> and [[Karol Irzykowski]] among others.<ref name="crvp.org" /> [[File:Siedziba Telewizji Polskiej w Warszawie 2017.jpg|220px|thumbnail|left|[[Telewizja Polska|TVP]] Building in [[Warsaw]]]] {{See also|Culture in post-communist Poland}}
In the Polish context, postmodernism has been categorized by [[literary criticism|literary critics]] as the framework of [[Pluralism (political philosophy)|pluralism]] necessary for the success of European integration as far as post-national diversity and regional differences are concerned.<ref name="crvp.org" />
The official welcome of postmodernism in post-communist Poland was somewhat late; it met with severe impediments not so much from the former communist establishment as from [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] itself and the Catholic Church, both of which promoted "collectivist" rather than "liberal" values.<ref name="crvp.org" /> However, beginning in the 1990s and throughout the early 21st century, postmodernism began to take a firm hold especially in the realms of poetics and art theory. Polish architects (Czesław Bielecki, [[Telewizja Polska|TVP]]; Marek Budzyński) and selected filmmakers (i.e. [[Krzysztof Kieślowski|Kieślowski]], [[Juliusz Machulski|Machulski]], [[Agnieszka Holland]], [[:pl:Jan Komasa|Komasa]]: the ''[[Suicide Room]]'') contribute substantially to the Polish postmodernist {{nobreak|''anti-foundationalism''}} in popular culture.<ref name="crvp.org">{{cite web | url=http://www.crvp.org/book/Series04/IVA-34/chapter-7.htm | title=From ‘Socialist’ to Postmodern Pluralism in Poland | publisher=The Council for Research in Values and Philosophy (RVP) | work=Chapter 7 | date=Feb 13, 2009 | accessdate=March 18, 2013 | author=Eugeniusz Górski | format=[https://www.webcitation.org/6FDjBTl5h?url=http://www.crvp.org/book/Series04/IVA-34/chapter-7.htm WebCite query] | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110413225221/http://www.crvp.org/book/Series04/IVA-34/chapter-7.htm | archivedate=April 13, 2011 | df= }}</ref><ref name="Beinek">{{cite web | url=http://www.indiana.edu/~iuslavic/docs/P365_Spring2008_poster.pdf | title=Post-Communist Polish Culture (1989-Present) | publisher=Indiana University | work=Topics in Polish Literature and Culture (Slav-P365/565) | accessdate=March 23, 2013 | author=Prof. Justyna Beinek | format=PDF file, direct download 66 KB}}</ref>
==Artistic origins== Although postmodernism was widely promoted in the so-called ''Drugi obieg'' (the Second circulation) by [[Polish underground press]], it has also been criticized as [[amorphous]] by both, Catholic philosophers, as well as "fallen Marxists",<ref name="crvp.org" /> credited with the emergence of {{nobreak|'''''soc'''-postmodernism''}} in Poland&nbsp;– based on ''extreme relativism'' and bitter sense of humor (see [[Sławomir Mrożek|Mrożek]]).<ref name="Stephan">{{cite journal | title=Remembering Stalinism: Sławomir Mrożek's Portrait and his Autobiographical Writings | publisher=The Polish Institute of Arts and Sciences | work=The Polish Review | date=1994| year=2013 | author=Halina Stephan | jstor=25778784 | volume=39 | pages=131–148}}</ref> The continuous dialog extending well-beyond the [[Martial law in Poland]], eventually led to destruction of the totalitarian ideology, and the inevitable acceptance of ''pluralism'' over ''foundationalism'' in art theory.<ref name="Janaszek-Ivaničková" /><ref name="crvp.org" /><ref name="Dascal">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5aNwSImFZhUC&pg=PA239&dq=%22extreme+relativism%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=CytOUc7AEvLSiAKLmICIBw&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22extreme%20relativism%22&f=false | title=Crossing Cultures | publisher=BRILL | work=Cultural Relativism and Philosophy | year=1991 | accessdate=March 23, 2013 | author=Marcelo Dascal | page=239 | format=Google book preview | isbn=9004094334}}</ref>
Postmodernism entered Poland in the 1960s at the end of the [[Stalinism in Poland|Stalinist period]] (with [[Andrzej Wróblewski|Wróblewski]] having the greatest impact on postwar [[figurative painting]]).<ref name="culture.pl-Wróblewski ">{{cite web | url=http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-visual-arts-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/andrzej-wroblewski | title=Andrzej Wróblewski | publisher=Adam Mickiewicz Institute ''Culture.pl'' | work=Resources: Visual Arts | date=December 2001 | accessdate=March 27, 2013 | author=Małgorzata Kitowska-Łysiak, Institute of the Catholic University of Lublin }}</ref> It was coupled with the advent of [[conceptualism]], [[Pop art]], as well as {{nobreak|[[neo-expressionism]]}}. These new movements&nbsp;– beginning as unofficial political and artistic discourses&nbsp;– challenged the vast matrix of Polish institutionalized culture defined before 1989 by the one-party system and the use of [[Socialist realism in Poland|politically charged realism]] as method of social control.<ref name="Dziamski">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7oLWAAAAMAAJ&q=postmodernism | title=Postmodernizm | publisher=Instytut kultury, Warszawa | work=Encyklopedia kultury polskiej XX wieku, Od awangardy do postmodernizmu | year=1996 | accessdate=March 22, 2013 | author=Grzegorz Dziamski | isbn=838532321X}}</ref>
==See also== * [[History of Poland (1945–1989)]] * [[History of Poland (1989–present)]] * [[Modernism]] and [[Postmodernism]] * [[Polish literature]] * [[Socialist realism]]
