{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Roberta Smith | birth_name = | image = File:Roberta-Smith-Brooklyn-Museum.png | caption = Smith speaking at the Brooklyn Museum, 2014 | birth_date = {{birth year|1948}} | birth_place = [[New York City, New York]], United States | occupation = [[Art critic]] | language = <!-- English --> | nationality = United States | citizenship = | education = [[Grinnell College]] | alma_mater = | period = 1970s–present | genre = | subject = Art | movement = | notableworks = }}
'''Roberta Smith''' (born 1947) is co-chief [[art critic]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' and a lecturer on [[contemporary art]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/by/roberta-smith|title=Roberta Smith|date=2018-03-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-03-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>Christopher Bolen, [http://www.interviewmagazine.com/art/roberta-smith-jerry-saltz/ "Roberta Smith & Jerry Saltz"], ''Interview'' magazine, undated.</ref> She is the first woman to hold that position.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://observer.com/2011/09/roberta-smith-and-holland-cotter-named-co-chief-art-critics-of-the-new-york-times/|title=Roberta Smith and Holland Cotter Named Co-Chief Art Critics of The New York Times|date=2011-09-14|work=Observer|access-date=2018-03-18|language=en-US}}</ref>
==Early life== Born in [[New York City]] and raised in [[Lawrence, Kansas|Lawrence]], Kansas, Smith studied at [[Grinnell College]] in Iowa. Her career in the arts started in 1968 while an undergraduate summer intern at the [[Corcoran Gallery of Art]] in Washington D.C. In 1968-69 she participated in the Art History/Museum Studies track of the [[Whitney Museum of American Art#Independent study program|Whitney Independent Study Program]] (ISP) where she met [[Donald Judd]] and became interested in [[minimal art]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/262737522|title=Independent study program : 40 years : Whitney Museum of American Art, 1968-2008.|last=Art.|first=Whitney Museum of American|date=2008|publisher=Whitney Museum of American Art|isbn=9780874271584|edition= 1st|location=New York|oclc=262737522}}</ref>
==Career== After graduation, she returned to New York City in 1971 to take a secretarial job at the [[Museum of Modern Art]], followed by part-time assistant jobs to Judd and Paula Cooper in 1972. While at the [[Paula Cooper Gallery]] she wrote exhibition reviews for ''[[Artforum]]'', and subsequently for ''[[Art in America]]'', the ''[[Village Voice]]'' and other publications as well. She began writing for ''The New York Times'' in 1986, and became the co-chief art critic in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/28/insider/judy-chicago-dinner-part-art-reviews-times.html|title=From ‘Vicious’ to Celebratory: The Times’s Reviews of Judy Chicago’s ‘The Dinner Party’|last=Pilat|first=Kasia|date=2018-02-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-03-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=":0" />
Smith has written numerous essays for catalogues and [[monographs]] on contemporary artists, and wrote the featured essay in the Judd [[catalogue raisonné]] published by the [[National Gallery of Canada]] in 1975. She writes not only about contemporary art but about the visual arts in general, including [[decorative arts]], popular and [[outsider art]], [[design]] and [[architecture]].
==Personal life== Smith lives in New York City with her husband [[Jerry Saltz]], senior art critic for [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' Magazine]]. They were married in 1992.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.artnet.com/opinion/kenny-schachter-jerry-saltz-777836|title=Jerry Saltz and the Future of the Critic-Artist {{!}} artnet News|date=2016-12-09|work=artnet News|access-date=2018-03-18|language=en-US}}</ref>
==Awards== * 2003 [[Frank Jewett Mather]] Award for Art Criticism, [[College Art Association]].<ref name="caa">{{cite web|url=http://www.collegeart.org/awards/matherpast|title=Awards|publisher=The College Art Association|accessdate=11 October 2010}}</ref> * 2009 AICA/USA Distinguished Critic Lecture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.veralistcenter.org/engage/event/177/roberta-smith-criticism-a-life-sentence/|title=The Vera List Center for Arts and Politics {{!}} Roberta Smith Criticism A Life Sentence|website=www.veralistcenter.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref> * 2014 Marina Kellen French Distinguished Visitor, The American Academy in Berlin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.americanacademy.de/person/roberta-smith/|title=Roberta Smith - American Academy|work=American Academy|access-date=2018-03-18|language=en-US}}</ref>
